GAUTENG has recorded the highest number of arrests for drinking and driving since the beginning of the festive season. From the beginning of the month until Friday, 1 639 motorists have bust for driving under the influence of alcohol. A total of 3 078 motorists were arrested across the country during the first 16 days of December for drunk driving, speeding, reckless and negligent driving, as well as possession of fake documents. According to the Road Traffic Management Corporation, among those bust were two motorists who allegedly tried to bribe a traffic cop in the Eastern Cape, and a motorist who was caught driving at 219km/h in a 120km/h zone on the N3 near Warden, Free State. Traffic cops conducted 258 roadblocks in all provinces and issued traffic fines to 152 243 motorists. More than 10 000 drivers were warned for failing to wear seatbelts, while 1 426 were given fines for talking on their cellphones while driving. There will be more roadblocks and law enforcement operations this weekend, as motorists will be travelling to see relatives for Christmas or going on holiday.- High volumes of traffic were experienced on Thursday and Friday, as many workers travelled back to their rural homes. On both days, more than 2 000 cars per hour were recorded passing through tollgates on the N3 south towards the coast between 10am and 8pm.The Road Traffic Management Corporation said: &ldquo;Traffic cops plan to clamp down on road traffic violations over the Christmas weekend to reduce crashes, injuries and fatalities. Motorists are urged to exercise caution, to be aware of pedestrians and to respect the rules of the road.&rdquo;